liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Financial crime regulator AUSTRAC will take no further action against Bell Financial Group after finalising its external audit of the company. Last February, AUSTRAC appointed an external auditor to examine Bell Financial's three entities (Bell Potter Securities, Bell Potter Capital and Third Party Platform ) to examine their compliance with with anti-money laundering and counter-terrorism financing laws. AUSTRAC has since been handed the final audit report, and has decided not to take any further regulatory action against the entities — finalising the external audit process. "AUSTRAC has reiterated the importance for Bell to meet its compliance obligations in the future, and will continue to work with Bell to ensure ongoing compliance, and to monitor the remediation and uplift undertaken by the entities in response to the external auditor findings and recommendations," the regulator said in a statement.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: AUSTRAC to take no further action against Bell Financial Group

children.content: Financial crime regulator AUSTRAC will take no further action against Bell Financial Group after finalising its external audit of the company.

Last February, AUSTRAC appointed an external auditor to examine Bell Financial's three entities (Bell Potter Securities, Bell Potter Capital and Third Party Platform ) to examine their compliance with with anti-money laundering and counter-terrorism financing laws.
AUSTRAC has since been handed the final audit report, and has decided not to take any further regulatory action against the entities — finalising the external audit process.

"AUSTRAC has reiterated the importance for Bell to meet its compliance obligations in the future, and will continue to work with Bell to ensure ongoing compliance, and to monitor the remediation and uplift undertaken by the entities in response to the external auditor findings and recommendations," the regulator said in a statement.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: We're in the depths of winter here in Australia, but let's take a quick (virtual) journey to summery Europe. Here's a quick roundup of major developments over there while we were sleeping: The STOXX 600 edged up, led by major gains for Swedish retailer H & M — the company posted stronger than expected profits for Q2, and sent their share price soaring by 18.2% as a result (more on this a bit later) Inflation in Germany rose by 6.8% in June, more than economists were predicting — although some analysts believe it's a blip in what's otherwise been a steady decline Sticking with inflation, it's dropped to 1.9% in Spain in June, making it the slowest increase in the country since March 2021. It also makes Spain one of the first major European economies to dip below 2%
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Inflation rises in Germany, but falls below 2pc in Spain

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Good morning and happy end of financial year to you — it's Friday, June 30 and you're reading the ABC's business and markets blog. Let's get you up to speed with the major developments from the US overnight: Stronger than expected economic data and new comments from Federal Reserve chair Jerome Powell has stoked fears more rate rises are on the way in the US — he told an event in Madrid the Fed's expectation is for "the moderate pace of interest rate decisions to continue" The data has also eased potential recession fears, thanks to Treasury yields pushing higher and leading investors to economically sensitive sectors Major banks were also up at the end of trade, after the lenders cleared the Fed's annual stress test The tech-heavy Nasdaq finished flat, after major tech companies including Microsoft, Amazon, Meta and Nvidia suffered losses throughout the day So what does Friday have in store for us locally? The ASX is looking like it will open slightly higher with futures up modestly, but it's looking to be a fairly subdued day as we race towards the end of the financial year. One piece of data that's coming out that we'll be keeping an eye on is private sector credit, which will give us a snapshot into housing lending for May. We'll have those figures at 11:30am AEST from the ABS. And it would be remiss of me not to mention the *other* big news of the day — Taylor Swift tickets going on general sale. Good luck if you're one of the four million Aussies braving the queue for the first (or second, or third, or fourth) time. Let's dive on in. (If you're not a Swiftie and need some context, that's her swan diving on stage.)
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX to open higher as US poised for future rate hikes

children.content: Good morning and happy end of financial year to you — it's
Friday, June 30
and you're reading the ABC's business and markets blog.
Let's get you up to speed with the major developments from the US overnight:
Stronger than expected economic data and new comments from Federal Reserve chair Jerome Powell has stoked fears
more rate rises are on the way in the US
— he told an event in Madrid the Fed's expectation is for "the moderate pace of interest rate decisions to continue"
The data has also eased potential recession fears, thanks to Treasury yields pushing higher and leading investors to economically sensitive sectors
Major banks were also up at the end of trade, after the lenders cleared the Fed's annual stress test
The tech-heavy Nasdaq finished flat, after major tech companies including Microsoft, Amazon, Meta and Nvidia suffered losses throughout the day

So what does Friday have in store for us locally? The ASX is looking like it will open slightly higher with futures up modestly, but it's looking to be a fairly subdued day as we race towards the end of the financial year.
One piece of data that's coming out that we'll be keeping an eye on is
private sector credit
, which will give us a snapshot into housing lending for May. We'll have those figures at 11:30am AEST from the ABS.
And it would be remiss of me not to mention the *other* big news of the day —
Taylor Swift tickets going on general sale
. Good luck if you're one of the four million Aussies braving the queue for the first (or second, or third, or fourth) time.
Let's dive on in.
(If you're not a Swiftie and need some context, that's her swan diving on stage.)
